Dataset Cuthbert_2020

This dataset from Cuthbert et al.Â (2020) is published in Cuthbert et al.Â (2023): https://doi.org/10.6084/m9.figshare.24598950.v1

  • Contains n=115 feeding trials. No single-prey experiments for prey 2.
  • Raw data is available.
  • Single- and multi-prey experiments ran for 2 hours, except for additional multi-prey experiments with constant total number of prey N1+N2=30, which ran for 0.5 hour.
  • Eaten prey were not replaced.
  • We fitted ODE-based predictions to the data.
  • Holling-2 was identified as the best fitting model. Other models performed equally.
  • The model predicts a preference for prey 2, no switching.
  • Multi-prey data from 2h experiments were rather over-predicted, while multi-prey data from 0.5h experiments were systematically under-predicted.

Prepare data

df.all includes all observations, df.switch only multi-species 0.5h experiments, df.multi only 2h multi-species experiments, df.single.1 only 2h single-species experiments, and df.both all multi-species experiments (2h and 0.5h).

Data has to be coded as a named list for Stan. Varying duration Time is provided, and all experiments were conducted without prey replacement Replaced=0.

data.stan = list(n = nrow(df.all),
                 m = 2,
                 N_0 = df.all[, 1:2],
                 N_e = df.all[, 3:4],
                 Time = df.all$Time,
                 Replaced = rep(0, nrow(df.all))
)

Model fitting

For all models, posterior distributions are sampled using 3 chains, 1000 warmup steps and 2000 sampling steps, each. Initial values init are provided for all parameters. Convergence of MCMC is verified through Rhat value close to 1 and sufficient number of effective samples n_eff.

chains = 3

Fit Holling 2

init = rep(list(list(a = c(1.0,1.0),
                     h = c(1/10,1/10))
),chains)

fit1 = sampling(
  model.H2,
  data = data.stan,
  chains = chains,
  warmup = 1000,
  iter = 3000,
  cores = 3,
  init = init,
  refresh = 100
)
print(fit1, pars=c("a","h"))

Model comparison

Extract log-likelihood values for all fits and compute predictive performance with leave-one-out cross validation using the loo package.

lik1 = extract_log_lik(fit1, merge_chains=FALSE)
reff1 = relative_eff(exp(lik1), cores=4) 
loo1 = loo(lik1, r_eff=reff1, cores=4)

lik2 = extract_log_lik(fit2, merge_chains=FALSE)
reff2 = relative_eff(exp(lik2), cores=4) 
loo2 = loo(lik2, r_eff=reff2, cores=4)

lik3 = extract_log_lik(fit3, merge_chains=FALSE)
reff3 = relative_eff(exp(lik3), cores=4) 
loo3 = loo(lik3, r_eff=reff3, cores=4)

lik4 = extract_log_lik(fit4, merge_chains=FALSE)
reff4 = relative_eff(exp(lik4), cores=4) 
loo4 = loo(lik4, r_eff=reff4, cores=4)

loo_compare(loo1, loo2, loo3, loo4)
       elpd_diff se_diff
model1  0.0       0.0   
model3 -2.1       6.3   
model2 -2.3       1.2   
model4 -3.0       3.9

Posterior predictions for best fitting model

The correct MSFR model function is chosen for deSolve. 1000 samples from the posterior distribution are chosen randomly. For these, predictions are generated through numerical simulation of ODEs. Their median and 90% credible intervals are plotted against observed data.

MSFR = Holling2

n.post = 1000
n.pred = 20
post = as.matrix(fit1)[, 1:4]
set.seed(100)
post = post[sample(1:nrow(post),n.post), ]

Single-species prey 1

N10.pred = seq(0.1, 32, length.out=n.pred)
N1E.pred = matrix(NA, nrow=n.post, ncol=n.pred)

for(k in 1:n.post){
  params = list(a=post[k, 1:2], 
                h=post[k, 3:4],
                m=2)
  for(i in 1:n.pred){
    out = ode(y = c(N=c(N10.pred[i], 0.0)), times = c(0,2), func = MSFR, parms = params) 
    N1E.pred[k,i] = N10.pred[i]-out[2,2]
  }
}

N1E.pred.qs = apply(N1E.pred, 2, function(x) quantile(x, probs=c(0.05, 0.5, 0.95)))

plot(jitter(df.single.1$Prey1, factor=0.3), jitter(df.single.1$Prey1.Eaten, factor=0.3), xlim=c(0,32), ylim=c(0,15),
     xlab="Prey 1 offered", ylab="Prey 1 eaten",
     main="Single-species feeding: Prey 1 (2h)")
polygon( c(N10.pred, rev(N10.pred)), 
         c(N1E.pred.qs[1, ], rev(N1E.pred.qs[3, ])), 
         border=NA,
         col=adjustcolor("blue", alpha.f=0.2)
)
lines(N10.pred, N1E.pred.qs[2, ], col="blue", lwd=2)

Multi-species relative consumption

Multi-species predictions are computed along a gradient of relative composition of N1 and N2 with N1+N2=30. Seperate plots for 2h and 0.5h experiments.

N0.total = 30

N10.pred = seq(0, N0.total, length.out=n.pred)
N20.pred = N0.total-N10.pred
N1E.pred = matrix(NA, nrow=n.post, ncol=n.pred)
N2E.pred = matrix(NA, nrow=n.post, ncol=n.pred)

for(k in 1:n.post){
  params = list(a=post[k, 1:2], 
                h=post[k, 3:4],
                m=2)
  for(i in 1:n.pred){
    out = ode(y = c(N=c(N10.pred[i], N20.pred[i])), times = c(0,2), func = MSFR, parms = params) 
    N1E.pred[k,i] = N10.pred[i]-out[2,2]
    N2E.pred[k,i] = N20.pred[i]-out[2,3]
  }
}

N1E.pred.qs = apply(N1E.pred, 2, function(x) quantile(x, probs=c(0.05, 0.5, 0.95)))
N2E.pred.qs = apply(N2E.pred, 2, function(x) quantile(x, probs=c(0.05, 0.5, 0.95)))

# make relative 
N1E.pred.rel = matrix(NA, nrow=n.post, ncol=n.pred)
N2E.pred.rel = matrix(NA, nrow=n.post, ncol=n.pred)
for(k in 1:n.post){
  N1E.pred.rel[k, ] = N1E.pred[k, ]/(N1E.pred[k, ]+N2E.pred[k, ])
  N2E.pred.rel[k, ] = N2E.pred[k, ]/(N1E.pred[k, ]+N2E.pred[k, ])
}

N1E.pred.rel.qs = apply(N1E.pred.rel, 2, function(x) quantile(x, probs=c(0.05, 0.5, 0.95)))
N2E.pred.rel.qs = apply(N2E.pred.rel, 2, function(x) quantile(x, probs=c(0.05, 0.5, 0.95)))

plot(df.multi$Prey1/(df.multi$Prey1+df.multi$Prey2),
     df.multi$Prey1.Eaten/(df.multi$Prey1.Eaten+df.multi$Prey2.Eaten),
     xlim=c(0,1), ylim=c(0,1),
     xlab="Proportion prey 1 offered", ylab="Proportion prey 1 eaten",
     main="Multi-species preference (2h)")
abline(0,1)
polygon( c(N10.pred/N0.total, rev(N10.pred/N0.total)), 
         c(N1E.pred.rel.qs[1, ], rev(N1E.pred.rel.qs[3, ])), 
         border=NA,
         col=adjustcolor("blue", alpha.f=0.2)
)
lines(N10.pred/N0.total, N1E.pred.rel.qs[2, ], col="blue", lwd=2)

Multi-species observed vs.Â predicted

Additionally, median predicted numbers of eaten prey (N1E and N2E) are computed and plotted against observed data points. Seperate plots for 2h and 0.5h experiments.

N1E.pred = matrix(NA, nrow=n.post, ncol=nrow(df.multi))
N2E.pred = matrix(NA, nrow=n.post, ncol=nrow(df.multi))

for(k in 1:n.post){
  params = list(a=post[k, 1:2], 
                h=post[k, 3:4],
                m=2)
  for(i in 1:nrow(df.multi)){
    out = ode(y = c(N=c(df.multi$Prey1[i],df.multi$Prey2[i])), 
              times = c(0,df.multi$Time[i]), func = MSFR, parms = params) 
    N1E.pred[k,i] = df.multi$Prey1[i]-out[2,2]
    N2E.pred[k,i] = df.multi$Prey2[i]-out[2,3]
  }
}

N1E.pred.qs = apply(N1E.pred, 2, function(x) quantile(x, probs=c(0.05, 0.5, 0.95)))
N2E.pred.qs = apply(N2E.pred, 2, function(x) quantile(x, probs=c(0.05, 0.5, 0.95)))

plot(NULL, xlim=c(0,40), ylim=c(0,40), xlab="Predicted", ylab="Observed",
     main="Multi-species obs vs. pred (2h)")
points(N1E.pred.qs[2, ], df.multi$Prey1.Eaten, col="blue")
points(N2E.pred.qs[2, ], df.multi$Prey2.Eaten, col="red")
abline(0,1)

N1E.pred = matrix(NA, nrow=n.post, ncol=nrow(df.switch))
N2E.pred = matrix(NA, nrow=n.post, ncol=nrow(df.switch))

for(k in 1:n.post){
  params = list(a=post[k, 1:2], 
                h=post[k, 3:4],
                m=2)
  for(i in 1:nrow(df.switch)){
    out = ode(y = c(N=c(df.switch$Prey1[i],df.switch$Prey2[i])), 
              times = c(0,df.switch$Time[i]), func = MSFR, parms = params) 
    N1E.pred[k,i] = df.switch$Prey1[i]-out[2,2]
    N2E.pred[k,i] = df.switch$Prey2[i]-out[2,3]
  }
}

N1E.pred.qs = apply(N1E.pred, 2, function(x) quantile(x, probs=c(0.05, 0.5, 0.95)))
N2E.pred.qs = apply(N2E.pred, 2, function(x) quantile(x, probs=c(0.05, 0.5, 0.95)))

plot(NULL, xlim=c(0,15), ylim=c(0,15), xlab="Predicted", ylab="Observed",
     main="Multi-species obs vs. pred (0.5h)")
points(N1E.pred.qs[2, ], df.switch$Prey1.Eaten, col="blue")
points(N2E.pred.qs[2, ], df.switch$Prey2.Eaten, col="red")
abline(0,1)
